                        <par_12
                            jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                            sling:resourceType="wcm/foundation/components/parsys">
                            <container4
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-05-04T21:35:24.605-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>The biggest news about small cell lung cancer (SCLC) in the last 15 years is that there’s been no news at all. No improvement in survival rates, no new treatments approved1 and, making up only about 10 to 15 percent of all lung cancers&lt;sup>2&lt;/sup>, conversations around the topic until recently were limited. This aggressive form of lung cancer almost exclusively impacts smokers or former smokers and has a devastatingly low five-year survival rate of about two percent.&lt;sup>3&lt;/sup>&lt;br>&#xa;&lt;br>&#xa;Here are five reasons why SCLC is difficult to treat and ways researchers are trying to break the slow news cycle:&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <separator
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-05-04T21:36:06.400-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-05-04T21:36:06.400-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <title
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825668]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-05-04T21:35:42.808-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-05-13T01:03:01.425-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="1. Screening is uncommon"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h5"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-05-04T21:36:46.492-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Unlike mammograms that screen for breast cancer and colonoscopies to screen for colon cancer, there is no widespread screening process for lung cancer.&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <separator_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-05-04T21:36:06.400-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-05-04T21:36:06.400-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <title_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825668]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-05-04T21:35:42.808-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-05-13T01:03:09.658-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="2. Fast growing"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h5"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2_copy_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-05-04T21:37:57.158-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>All types of lung cancer are aggressive and typically spread to other parts of the body, but SCLC is particularly aggressive. Normal lung cells turn cancerous for two broad categories of reasons. Using car troubles as an analogy, they develop “brake” failures or lose control of the “engine RPM.” In some instances, it’s a combination of both.&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4>
